{{short description|Anglo-Irish poet and playwright}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}} {{Use British English|date=September 2012}} {{Infobox officeholder | name = Nahum Tate | image = Ntate.jpg | imagesize = 220px | office = [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom]] | monarch = [[William III of England|William III]] and [[Mary II]] | term_start = 23 December 1692 | term_end = 30 July 1715 | predecessor = [[Thomas Shadwell]] | successor = [[Nicholas Rowe (writer)|Nicholas Rowe]] | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Nahum Teate | birth_date = 1652 | birth_place = [[Dublin]], [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]] | death_date = {{Death year and age|1715 |1652}} | death_place = [[Southwark]], [[London]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great&nbsp;Britain]] | resting_place = [[Southwark St George]], [[London]] | occupation = [[Poet]] | language = [[English language|English]] | ethnicity = [[Irish people|Irish]] | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''[[The History of King Lear]]'' | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = [[Faithful Teate]] (father) | awards = [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom|Poet Laureate of the Kingdom&nbsp;of&nbsp;England]] ([[1692 in literature|1692]]) | signature = | signature_alt = | portaldisp = }}
'''Nahum Tate''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|n|eɪ|.|əm|_|ˈ|t|eɪ|t}} {{respell|NAY|əm|_|TAYT}}; 1652 – 30 July 1715) was an Irish [[poet]], [[hymnist]] and [[lyricist]], who became [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom|England's poet laureate]] in 1692. Tate is best known for ''[[The History of King Lear]]'', his 1681 [[literary adaptation|adaptation]] of Shakespeare's ''[[King Lear]]''.
==Life== Nahum Tate was born in [[Dublin]] and came from a family of [[Puritan]] clerics. He was the son of [[Faithful Teate]], an Irish cleric<ref name="life1">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/nutter/hymnwriters.Tate_Nah.html%0A%09 |title=hymnwriters |access-date=13 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060104075549/http://www.ccel.org/ccel/nutter/hymnwriters.Tate_Nah.html |archive-date=4 January 2006 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> who had been rector of [[Castleterra]], [[Ballyhaise]], until his house was burnt and his family attacked after he had passed on information to the government about plans for the [[Irish Rebellion of 1641]].
After living at the provost's lodgings in [[Trinity College, Dublin]], Faithful Teate moved to England. He was the [[incumbent (ecclesiastical)|incumbent]] at [[Greenwich|East Greenwich]] around 1650, and "preacher of the gospel" at [[Sudbury, London|Sudbury]] from 1654 to 1658. He had returned to Dublin by 1660. He published a poem on the Trinity entitled ''Ter Tria'',<ref>''Ter Tria, or the Doctrine of the Three Sacred Persons, Father, Son, and Holy Spirit; Principal Graces, Faith, Hope, and Love; Main Duties, Prayer, Hearing, and Meditation''</ref> as well as some sermons, two of which he dedicated to [[Oliver Cromwell|Oliver]] and [[Henry Cromwell]].<ref name="dnb">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Tate, Nahum|first=Henry Leigh|last=Bennett}}</ref>
Nahum Teate followed his father to Trinity College, Dublin in 1668, and graduated BA in 1672. By 1676 he had moved to London and was writing for a living. The following year he had adopted the spelling "Tate", which would remain until his death. He died in 1715, in Southwark, London, England.<ref name="nndb">{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/448/000098154/|title=Nahum Tate|work=nndb.com}}</ref> He was buried at [[St George the Martyr, Southwark]] on 1 August 1715 as 'of next to the Prince Eugene, Mint'.{{clarify|date=September 2018}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.ancestry.co.uk/Browse/View.aspx?dbid=1624&path=Southwark.St+George+the+Martyr.1695-1732.237|title=Pay as you go|work=ancestry.co.uk}}</ref>
==Works== [[File:LearTate.jpg|thumb|Cover of [[The History of King Lear|Tate's version of ''King Lear'']]]] Tate published a volume of poems in London in 1677, and became a regular writer for the stage. ''Brutus of Alba, or The Enchanted Lovers'' (1678), a tragedy dealing with [[Dido]] and [[Aeneas]], was dedicated to [[Charles Sackville, 6th Earl of Dorset]];<ref name=dnb/> it was later adapted as the libretto for [[Henry Purcell]]'s opera ''[[Dido and Æneas|Dido and Aeneas]]'' (1688 or earlier).<ref name="nndb"/> ''The Loyal General'', with a prologue by [[John Dryden|Dryden]], played at the [[Dorset Garden Theatre]] in 1680.<ref name=dnb/>
Tate then turned to making a series of adaptations of Elizabethan dramas. His version of [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' altered the names of the characters, and changed the text so that every scene, to use his own words, was "full of respect to Majesty and the dignity of courts"; but in spite of these precautions ''The Sicilian Usurper'' (1681), as his rewrite was called, was suppressed on the third performance on account of a possible political interpretation.<ref name="nndb"/> In 1681 [[Thomas Betterton]] played Tate's version of ''[[King Lear]]'',<ref name=dnb/> which entirely omitted the Fool, and [[Happy ending|ended happily]] in marriage between [[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]] and Edgar.<ref name="kl">{{cite web|url=http://andromeda.rutgers.edu/~jlynch/Texts/tatelear.html|title=Nahum Tate, King Lear|work=rutgers.edu}}</ref> (Though [[Joseph Addison]] protested at this mutilation of Shakespeare, [[Samuel Johnson]] defended the poetic justice of Tate's adaptation.)<ref name=dnb/>''[[Coriolanus (play)|Coriolanus]]'' became ''The Ingratitude of a Commonwealth'', played at the [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]] in 1682. Tate's [[farce]] ''Duke and no Duke'' (first printed 1685, but acted earlier at the Theatre Royal) imitated Sir [[Aston Cockayne]]'s ''Trappolin suppos'd a Prince''. His ''Cuckold's Haven'' (performed 1685 at the Theatre Royal) was derived from [[George Chapman|Chapman]] and [[John Marston (poet)|Marston]]'s ''[[Eastward Hoe|Eastward Ho]]''. ''The Island Princess, or the Generous Portugals'' (1687) was adapted from [[John Fletcher (playwright)|John Fletcher]]. ''Injur'd Love, or the Cruel Husband'' (1707), altered from [[John Webster|Webster]]'s ''[[The White Devil]]'', seems never to have been acted.<ref name=dnb/>
In 1682 Tate collaborated with [[John Dryden]] to complete the second half of his epic poem ''[[Absalom and Achitophel]]''.<ref name="aba">{{cite web| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060502081228/http://rpo.library.utoronto.ca/poem/737.html |url=http://rpo.library.utoronto.ca/poem/737.html Absalom | archivedate= 2006-05-02 |title= Absalom and Achitophel: The Second Part |quote= The success of ''Absalom and Achitophel'' was so great that Dryden was pressed by several persons to continue his satirical commentary upon the times. This he declined to do but he engaged his friend Nahum Tate (1652–1715), the poet and dramatist, to write a second part to ''Absalom and Achitophel''. He supervised and revised the whole poem and added the verses characterizing Thomas Shadwell and Elkanah Settle as Og and Doeg.|year= 2005| author= Ian Lancashire |work= Representative Poetry Online| publisher=[[University of Toronto Libraries]] }}</ref>
Tate wrote the [[libretto]] for [[Henry Purcell]]'s [[opera]] ''[[Dido and Aeneas]]''; its first known performance was in 1689. He also wrote the text for Purcell's Birthday Ode ''[[Come Ye Sons of Art]]'' in 1694. Tate also translated ''Syphilis sive Morbus Gallicus'', [[Girolamo Fracastoro]]'s [[Latin]] [[pastoral]] poem on the subject of the disease of [[syphilis]], into English [[heroic couplet]]s.
Tate's name is also connected with the famous ''[[Tate and Brady|New Version of the Psalms of David]]'' (1696), for which he collaborated with [[Nicholas Brady (poet)|Nicholas Brady]]. Some items such as "As pants the hart" ([[Psalm 42]]) rise above the general level, and are said to be Tate's work.<ref name="nndb"/> A supplement was licensed in 1703 which included the [[Christmas carol]] "[[While Shepherds Watched Their Flocks]]", one of a number of hymns by Tate.
His poems were sharply criticised by [[Alexander Pope]] in ''[[The Dunciad]]''.
Of his numerous poems the most original is ''Panacea, a poem on Tea'' (1700). In spite of his consistent [[Toryism]], he succeeded [[Thomas Shadwell|Shadwell]] as [[poet laureate]] in 1692. He died within the precincts of the Mint, [[Southwark]], where he had taken refuge from his creditors, in 1715.<ref name="nndb"/>
==Modern stagings== {{refimprove section|date=February 2015}} In 1985, the [[Riverside Shakespeare Company]] of New York City staged Tate's ''[[The History of King Lear|History of King Lear]]'' in its original form, "happy ending" and all, directed by W. Stuart McDowell at [[The Shakespeare Center]].<ref>Mel Gussow. "Tate's ''Lear'' at Riverside", ''The New York Times'', 5 April 1985, and Howard Kissel. "''King Lear'' for Optimists", ''Women's Wear Daily'', 22 March 1985.</ref> This included removing the Fool altogether, adding a [[confidante]] for Cordelia, named Arante, as well as an "abduction" scene of Cordelia on the heath. The play concluded with multiple happy endings: for Lear and Kent, and Cordelia and Edgar, who presumably wed after the play's conclusion. Musical interludes were sung by cast members during the act breaks, accompanied by a [[harpsichord]] in the [[orchestra pit]].
